Confirmed this also happens in the stable 15.2.0 next release 
```
TypeError: The "path" argument must be of type string. Received undefined
@api:dev:     at [project]/packages/database/prisma/client/runtime/library.js [app-route] (ecmascript) (../../packages/database/prisma/client/runtime/library.js:6:1430)
@api:dev:     at [project]/packages/database/prisma/client/index.js [app-route] (ecmascript) (../../packages/database/prisma/client/index.js:26:1)
@api:dev:     at [project]/apps/api/lib/db/prisma.ts [app-route] (ecmascript) (lib/db/prisma.ts:1:0)
```

Same behaviour with the [@google-cloud/logging-winston](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@google-cloud/logging-winston) package

import { LoggingWinston } from '@google-cloud/logging-winston';

Will also throw the [turbopack] TypeError: The "path" argument must be of type string. Received undefined error

for reference, we have our database as a package, and load it like thus:
```
import { PrismaClient } from "@company/database";

const globalForPrisma = global as unknown as {
  prisma: PrismaClient | undefined;
};

export const prisma = globalForPrisma.prisma ?? new PrismaClient({});

if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== "production") globalForPrisma.prisma = prisma;

export default prisma;

```
